{"title_page": "Edgenuity", "text_new": "{{Infobox dot-com company\n| name          = Edgenuity\n| logo          = \n| type          = \n| traded_as     = \n| foundation    = {{start date and age|1998}}\n| founder       = \n| location      = {{Nowrap|[[Scottsdale, Arizona|Scottsdale]], [[Arizona]], U.S.}}\n| key_people    = Sari Factor, CEO\n| services      = [[Online education]]\n| revenue       = \n| net_income    = \n| assets        = \n| equity        = \n| num_employees = \n| website       = {{URL|https://www.edgenuity.com/}}\n| alexa         = \n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Edgenuity''', formerly '''E2020''', is a standard-based [[Distance learning|online learning]] resource for school districts,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Price |first1=Chevall |title=Cy-Fair ISD parents adjust to learning at home |url=https://www.chron.com/neighborhood/cyfair/schools/article/Northwest-Houston-parent-adjust-to-Edgenuity-15162569.php |publisher=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> which teaches kindergarten through 12th-grade<ref>{{cite web |last1=Guidry |first1=Leigh |title=Have a graduating senior? Lafayette Parish releases info about grade recovery, requirements |url=https://www.theadvertiser.com/story/news/local/education/2020/04/22/lafayette-parish-provides-guidance-grades-graduating-seniors/3008202001/ |publisher=Lafayette Daily |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=22 April 2020}}</ref> in core, elective, credit recovery, technical, and career subjects, through both remedial and accelerated work.<ref>{{cite web |last1=LaRoue |first1=Jimmy |title=Division rolls out learning plan |url=https://www.suffolknewsherald.com/2020/03/30/division-rolls-out-learning-plan/ |publisher=Suffolk Herald News |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=E2020 Changes Name to Edgenuity, Releases New Platform |url=https://thejournal.com/articles/2013/02/06/e2020-changes-name-to-edgenuity-releases-new-platform.aspx |accessdate=23 April 2020 |agency=The Journal |publisher=Tim Sohn}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nEdgenuity was founded in 1998 as Education2020 Inc. (E2020).<ref name=\":hist\">{{cite web |last1=Molnar |first1=Michelle |title=Edgenuity Acquires Compass Learning to Expand Online, Blended Learning Reach |url=https://marketbrief.edweek.org/marketplace-k-12/edgenuity-acquires-compass-learning-expand-online-blended-learning-reach/ |publisher=Edweek |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=1 August 2016}}</ref> In 2011, Edgenuity was purchased by the company Weld North for an estimated 50 million dollars.<ref name=\":hist\" />\n\nEdgenuity was a popular tool for remote learning during the [[2019-20 Coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=LaRoue |first1=Jimmy |title=Board adopts grading plan |url=https://www.suffolknewsherald.com/2020/04/10/board-adopts-grading-plan/ |publisher=Suffolk News Herald |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Schools to remain closed, EPSB makes online resources available |url=https://www.villeplattetoday.com/news-covid-19/schools-remain-closed-epsb-makes-online-resources-available |publisher=Evangeline Today |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=23 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Stansell |first1=Kaitlin |title=Berkeley Co. teachers will use upcoming \u2018workday\u2019 for blended learning preparations |url=https://www.live5news.com/2020/04/01/berkeley-co-teachers-will-use-upcoming-workday-blended-learning-preparations/ |publisher=Live 5 News |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> It was unable to maintain the sharp increase in users, and many schools using the software reported problems with it.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ray |first1=Payne |title=Lake schools closed till May 1, distance-learning continues |url=https://www.dailycommercial.com/news/20200331/lake-schools-closed-till-may-1-distance-learning-continues |publisher=Daily Commercial |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Travis |first1=Scott |title=Broward schools online education platform crashes on first day |url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/coronavirus/fl-ne-broward-schoools-online-educatoin-crashes-20200330-prysaa2lczeotiibp3lcdzphqe-story.html |publisher=South Florida Sun Sentinel |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Education style ==\nEdgenuity mainly focuses on engaging content, primarily working with productivity and efficiency of struggling students, and working with them at their own pace.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Griffith |first1=Kristen |title=St. Mary's online resources viewed as school closure continues |url=https://www.somdnews.com/emergency_notice/st-marys-online-resources-viewed-as-school-closure-continues/article_5905c44f-2961-5b4c-9246-6dcf6be17fb2.html |publisher=Southern Maryland News |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> Edgenuity engages with the student using interactives, manipulations, and real-world problems.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Riddel |first1=Roger |title=Edgenuity CEO talks personalized learning and classroom tech [ISTE] |url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/edgenuity-ceo-talks-personalized-learning-and-classroom-tech-iste/283165/ |publisher=Education Dive |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=9 July 2014}}</ref> The software is also used by schools to help students who have failed courses get the credits they are missing.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Levin |first1=Ari |title=Espa\u00f1ola Schools Finishing Year Remotely |url=http://www.riograndesun.com/news/espa-ola-schools-finishing-year-remotely/article_b1a5273a-7a6d-11ea-a0d1-07cb9e88d1c7.html |publisher=Rio Grande Sun |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nEdgenuity CEO Sari Factor was a Gold Winner out of 700 nominations in the Executive of the Year category in the 9th Annual \"Best in Biz Awards\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Edgenuity CEO Sari Factor Named Gold Winner, Executive Of The Year By Best In Biz Awards |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/edgenuity-ceo-sari-factor-named-150000083.html |website=Yahoo Finance |publisher=PR Newswire |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nEdgenuity has been criticized for the standardization of their test questions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greene |first1=Peter |title=As Schools Tackle Coronavirus Pause, Don\u2019t Forget Career And Technical Education Students. |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/petergreene/2020/04/01/as-schools-take-coronavirus-pause-dont-forget-career-and-technical-education-students/#28df5e883fb7 |publisher=Forbes |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> This makes it easy for students to find test answers online while taking a test. In addition, the nature of the standardization causes students who fail a test to receive a very similar test the second time, making it easy to guess answers based on trial and error. A study published by [[Slate (magazine)|Slate Magazine]] showed that students received on average 37 out of 50 identical questions during their second attempt to pass a test.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smiley |first1=Stephen |title=Just Take It Again |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2017/05/are-online-credit-recovery-courses-too-easy-to-game.html |publisher=Slate |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Classroom management software]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1998]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox dot-com company\n| name          = Edgenuity\n| logo          = \n| type          = \n| traded_as     = \n| foundation    = {{start date and age|1998}}\n| founder       = \n| location      = {{Nowrap|[[Scottsdale, Arizona|Scottsdale]], [[Arizona]], U.S.}}\n| key_people    = Sari Factor, CEO\n| services      = [[Online education]]\n| revenue       = \n| net_income    = \n| assets        = \n| equity        = \n| num_employees = \n| website       = {{URL|https://www.edgenuity.com/}}\n| alexa         = \n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Edgenuity''', formerly '''E2020''', is a standard-based [[Distance learning|online learning]] resource for school districts,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Price |first1=Chevall |title=Cy-Fair ISD parents adjust to learning at home |url=https://www.chron.com/neighborhood/cyfair/schools/article/Northwest-Houston-parent-adjust-to-Edgenuity-15162569.php |publisher=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> which teaches kindergarten through 12th-grade<ref>{{cite web |last1=Guidry |first1=Leigh |title=Have a graduating senior? Lafayette Parish releases info about grade recovery, requirements |url=https://www.theadvertiser.com/story/news/local/education/2020/04/22/lafayette-parish-provides-guidance-grades-graduating-seniors/3008202001/ |publisher=Lafayette Daily |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=22 April 2020}}</ref> in core, elective, credit recovery, technical, and career subjects, through both remedial and accelerated work.<ref>{{cite web |last1=LaRoue |first1=Jimmy |title=Division rolls out learning plan |url=https://www.suffolknewsherald.com/2020/03/30/division-rolls-out-learning-plan/ |publisher=Suffolk Herald News |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=E2020 Changes Name to Edgenuity, Releases New Platform |url=https://thejournal.com/articles/2013/02/06/e2020-changes-name-to-edgenuity-releases-new-platform.aspx |accessdate=23 April 2020 |agency=The Journal |publisher=Tim Sohn}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nEdgenuity was founded in 1998 as Education2020 Inc. (E2020).<ref name=\":hist\">{{cite web |last1=Molnar |first1=Michelle |title=Edgenuity Acquires Compass Learning to Expand Online, Blended Learning Reach |url=https://marketbrief.edweek.org/marketplace-k-12/edgenuity-acquires-compass-learning-expand-online-blended-learning-reach/ |publisher=Edweek |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=1 August 2016}}</ref> In 2011, Edgenuity was purchased by the company Weld North for an estimated 50 million.<ref name=\":hist\" />\n\nEdgenuity was a popular tool for remote learning during the [[2019-20 Coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=LaRoue |first1=Jimmy |title=Board adopts grading plan |url=https://www.suffolknewsherald.com/2020/04/10/board-adopts-grading-plan/ |publisher=Suffolk News Herald |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Schools to remain closed, EPSB makes online resources available |url=https://www.villeplattetoday.com/news-covid-19/schools-remain-closed-epsb-makes-online-resources-available |publisher=Evangeline Today |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=23 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Stansell |first1=Kaitlin |title=Berkeley Co. teachers will use upcoming \u2018workday\u2019 for blended learning preparations |url=https://www.live5news.com/2020/04/01/berkeley-co-teachers-will-use-upcoming-workday-blended-learning-preparations/ |publisher=Live 5 News |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> It was unable to maintain the sharp increase in users, and many schools using the software reported problems with it.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ray |first1=Payne |title=Lake schools closed till May 1, distance-learning continues |url=https://www.dailycommercial.com/news/20200331/lake-schools-closed-till-may-1-distance-learning-continues |publisher=Daily Commercial |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Travis |first1=Scott |title=Broward schools online education platform crashes on first day |url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/coronavirus/fl-ne-broward-schoools-online-educatoin-crashes-20200330-prysaa2lczeotiibp3lcdzphqe-story.html |publisher=South Florida Sun Sentinel |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Education style ==\nEdgenuity mainly focuses on engaging content, primarily working with productivity and efficiency of struggling students, and working with them at their own pace.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Griffith |first1=Kristen |title=St. Mary's online resources viewed as school closure continues |url=https://www.somdnews.com/emergency_notice/st-marys-online-resources-viewed-as-school-closure-continues/article_5905c44f-2961-5b4c-9246-6dcf6be17fb2.html |publisher=Southern Maryland News |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> Edgenuity engages with the student using interactives, manipulations, and real-world problems.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Riddel |first1=Roger |title=Edgenuity CEO talks personalized learning and classroom tech [ISTE] |url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/edgenuity-ceo-talks-personalized-learning-and-classroom-tech-iste/283165/ |publisher=Education Dive |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=9 July 2014}}</ref> The software is also used by schools to help students who have failed courses get the credits they are missing.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Levin |first1=Ari |title=Espa\u00f1ola Schools Finishing Year Remotely |url=http://www.riograndesun.com/news/espa-ola-schools-finishing-year-remotely/article_b1a5273a-7a6d-11ea-a0d1-07cb9e88d1c7.html |publisher=Rio Grande Sun |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nEdgenuity CEO Sari Factor was a Gold Winner out of 700 nominations in the Executive of the Year category in the 9th Annual \"Best in Biz Awards\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Edgenuity CEO Sari Factor Named Gold Winner, Executive Of The Year By Best In Biz Awards |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/edgenuity-ceo-sari-factor-named-150000083.html |website=Yahoo Finance |publisher=PR Newswire |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nEdgenuity has been criticized for the standardization of their test questions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greene |first1=Peter |title=As Schools Tackle Coronavirus Pause, Don\u2019t Forget Career And Technical Education Students. |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/petergreene/2020/04/01/as-schools-take-coronavirus-pause-dont-forget-career-and-technical-education-students/#28df5e883fb7 |publisher=Forbes |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> This makes it easy for students to find test answers online while taking a test. In addition, the nature of the standardization causes students who fail a test to receive a very similar test the second time, making it easy to guess answers based on trial and error. A study published by [[Slate (magazine)|Slate Magazine]] showed that students received on average 37 out of 50 identical questions during their second attempt to pass a test.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smiley |first1=Stephen |title=Just Take It Again |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2017/05/are-online-credit-recovery-courses-too-easy-to-game.html |publisher=Slate |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Classroom management software]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1998]]\n", "name_user": "Hillelfrei", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edgenuity"}
{"title_page": "Stomatolina rubra", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| taxon = Stomatolina rubra\n| image = Stomatolina rubra 001.jpg\n| image_caption = Drawing with three views of a s shell of ''Stomatolina rubra''\n| authority =  (Lamarck, 1822)\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"WoRMS\" />\n| synonyms =\n* ''Microtis rubra'' <small>(Deshayes, 1843)</small>\n* ''Pseudostomatella rubra'' <small>(Lamarck, 1822)</small>\n* ''Stomatia rubra'' <small>Lamarck, 1822</small>\n| display_parents = 3\n}}\n\n'''''Stomatolina rubra''''', common name the '''red stomatolina''', is a [[species]] of small [[sea snail]], a marine [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Trochidae]], the top snails.<ref name=\"WoRMS\">{{WRMS species|213528|''Stomatolina rubra'' (Lamarck, 1822)||13 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe size of the shell varies between 8&nbsp;mm and 18&nbsp;mm. The depressed, rather thin shell has a small, conical [[Spire (mollusc)|spire]]. It is reddish brown, lighter beneath, or variously variegated. The surface is covered with close fine hair-like spiral striae, and with two low keels above the periphery, the upper one nodose. There is a series of short folds below the [[Suture (anatomy)|suture]]. The [[Whorl (mollusc)|whorl]]s of the spire contain a beaded carina. The wide [[body whorl]] is depressed, flattened above, convex below, and impressed at the axis. The large [[Aperture (mollusc)|aperture]] is rounded, very oblique, and iridescent within.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/manualconch12tryorich H.A. Pilsbry (1890) Manual of Conchology XII; Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia, 1890] (described as ''Stomatia rubra'')</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThis marine species occurs in the tropical Indo-West Pacific and off [[Korea]], the [[Philippines]] and Australia ([[Northern Territory]], [[Queensland]], [[Western Australia]])\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Wilson, B. 1993. ''Australian Marine Shells. Prosobranch Gastropods''. Kallaroo, Western Australia : Odyssey Publishing Vol. 1 408 pp\n* Poppe G.T., Tagaro S.P. & Dekker H. (2006) ''The Seguenziidae, Chilodontidae, Trochidae, Calliostomatidae and Solariellidae of the Philippine Islands''. Visaya Supplement 2: 1\u2013228. page(s): 104\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gastropods.com|key=9|id=2419|title=''Stomatolina rubra''|access-date=16 January 2019}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q7618740}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stomatolina Rubra}}\n[[Category:Stomatolina|rubra]]\n[[Category:Gastropods described in 1822]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| taxon = Stomatolina rubra\n| image = Stomatolina rubra 001.jpg\n| image_caption = Drawing with three views of a s shell of ''Stomatolina rubra''\n| authority =  (Lamarck, 1822)\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"WoRMS\" />\n| synonyms =\n* ''Microtis rubra'' <small>(Deshayes, 1843)</small>\n* ''Pseudostomatella rubra'' <small>(Lamarck, 1822)</small>\n* ''Stomatia rubra'' <small>Lamarck, 1822</small>\n| display_parents = 3\n}}\n\n'''''Stomatolina rubra''''', common name the '''red stomatolina''', is a [[species]] of small [[sea snail]], a marine [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Trochidae]], the top snails.<ref name=\"WoRMS\">{{WRMS species|213528|''Stomatolina rubra'' (Lamarck, 1822)||13 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe size of the shell varies between 8&nbsp;mm and 18&nbsp;mm. The depressed, rather thin shell has a small, conical [[Spire (mollusc)|spire]]. It is reddish brown, lighter beneath, or variously variegated. The surface is covered with close fine hair-like spiral striae, and with two low keels above the periphery, the upper one nodose. There is a series of short folds below the [[Suture (anatomy)|suture]]. The [[Whorl (mollusc)|whorl]]s of the spire contain a beaded carina. The wide  [[body whorl]] is depressed, flattened above, convex below, and impressed at the axis. The large [[Aperture (mollusc)|aperture]] is rounded, very oblique, and iridescent within.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/manualconch12tryorich H.A. Pilsbry (1890) Manual of Conchology XII; Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia, 1890] (described as ''Stomatia rubra'')</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThis marine species occurs in the tropical Indo-West Pacific and off [[Korea]], the [[Philippines]] and Australia ([[Northern Territory]], [[Queensland]], [[Western Australia]])\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Wilson, B. 1993. ''Australian Marine Shells. Prosobranch Gastropods''. Kallaroo, Western Australia : Odyssey Publishing Vol. 1 408 pp\n* Poppe G.T., Tagaro S.P. & Dekker H. (2006) ''The Seguenziidae, Chilodontidae, Trochidae, Calliostomatidae and Solariellidae of the Philippine Islands''. Visaya Supplement 2: 1-228. page(s): 104\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gastropods.com|key=9|id=2419|title=''Stomatolina rubra''|access-date=16 January 2019}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q7618740}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stomatolina Rubra}}\n[[Category:Stomatolina|rubra]]\n[[Category:Gastropods described in 1822]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing, date format audit,typo(s) fixed: 1-228 \u2192 1\u2013228", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stomatolina_rubra"}
{"title_page": "Stomatia phymotis", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| taxon = Stomatia phymotis\n| image = Stomatia phymotis 01.JPG\n| image_caption = Five views of a shell of ''Stomatia phymotis''\n| authority =  (Hebling, 1779) <ref>Helbling, G.S. 1779. ''Beitr\u00e4ge zur Kenntnis neuer seltener Konchylien. 102\u2013125, pl. 2 in Abhandlungen einer Privatgesellschaft in B\u00f6hmen zur Aufnahme der Mathematik, der v\u00e4terlandischen Geschichte, und der Naturgeschichte.'' Prag : Ignaz Edlen von Born Vol. 4</ref>\n| synonyms_ref = \n| synonyms =\n* ''Haliotis imperforata'' <small>Gmelin, 1791</small>\n* ''Stomatia australis'' <small>A. Adams, 1850</small>\n* ''Stomatia obscurata'' <small>Lamarck, 1822</small>\n* ''Stomatia (Miraconcha) obscura'' <small>Sowerby, G.B. III, 1874</small>\n* ''Stomax furonculus'' <small>Montfort</small>\n| display_parents = 3\n}}\n\n'''''Stomatia phymotis''''', common name the '''swollen stomatella''', is a [[species]] of [[sea snail]], a marine [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Trochidae]], the top snails.<ref name=\"WoRMS\">{{WRMS species|216287|''Stomatia phymotis'' (Hebling, 1779)||1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe size of the shell varies between 7&nbsp;mm and 35&nbsp;mm. The lengthened, solid shell is ear-shaped. It has a scalar spire. The [[body whorl]] descends very deeply. The shell is lusterless, red, marked at the [[Suture (anatomy)|suture]], keel and base with olive or brown articulated with white. The surface is very rough, with a strong double nodulous keel at the middle of the [[Whorl (mollusc)|whorl]], several nodose spiral riblets and threads below it, strongly. The shell is plicate or puckered below the sutures. The [[Aperture (mollusc)|aperture]] is irregular-oval and nacreous inside.\n\nThere is considerable variation in both form and color.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/manualconch12tryorich H.A. Pilsbry (1890) Manual of Conchology XII; Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia, 1890]</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThis marine species occurs in the [[Red Sea]], Central and East Indian Ocean, East India, Indo-Malaysia, [[Oceania]], the [[Philippines]], [[Japan]], [[Australia]] (Northern Territory, Queensland, Western Australia) and [[Indonesia]].<ref>{{cite book\n |url=https://www.amazon.com/Siput-Kerang-Indonesia-Indonesian-Shells/dp/B0010AHVB0\n |first1=Bunjamin |last1=Dharma\n |year=1988\n |title=Siput dan kerang Indonesia (Indonesian Shells)\n |volume=I. [A up to Olividae]\n |pages=111 pp\n |publisher=PT. Sarana Graha |location=[[Jakarta]]\n |accessdate=2017-03-14 |language=id,en }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Gmelin, J.F. & Linnaeus, C. 1791. ''Caroli a Linn\u00e9 Systema Naturae per regna tria naturae, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentis, synonymis, locis.'' Editio decima tertia aucta, reformata. Lipsiae : G.E. Beer.\n* Adams, A. 1850. ''An arrangement of Stomatellidae, including the characters of a new genus Cumingia, with some additional generic characters.'' Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London 1850(18): 29\u201340, pl. 8\n* Melvill, J.C. & Standen, R. 1901. ''The Mollusca of the Persian Gulf, Gulf of Oman, and the Arabian Sea, as evidenced mainly through the collections of Mr. F.W. Townsend, 1893\u20131900; with descriptions of new species''. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London 1901(ii): 327\u2013460 pls xxi\u2013xxiv \n* Allan, J. 1935. ''Australian shells: ear shells and wide-mouthed shells''. Australian Museum Magazine 5(9): 320\u2013324, 5 figs\n* Cotton, B.C. 1945. ''Southern Australian Gastropoda. Part 1. Streptoneura''. Transactions of the Royal Society of South Australia 69(1): 150\u2013171\n* Cotton, B.C. 1959. ''South Australian Mollusca. Archaeogastropoda''. Handbook of the Flora and Fauna of South Australia. Adelaide : South Australian Government Printer 449 pp\n* Maes, V.O. 1967. ''The littoral marine mollusks of Cocos-Keeling Islands (Indian Ocean).'' Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia 119: 93\u2013217\n* Cernohorsky, W.O. 1974. ''Type specimens of Mollusca in the University Zoological Museum Copenhagen''. Records of the Auckland Institute and Museum 11: 143\u2013195\n* Sharabati, D. 1984. ''Red Sea Shells''. London : KPI Limited 128 pp.\n* Wells, F.E. & Bryce, C.W. 1988. ''Seashells of Western Australia''. Perth : Western Australian Museum 207 pp.\n* Wilson, B. 1993. ''Australian Marine Shells. Prosobranch Gastropods.'' Kallaroo, Western Australia : Odyssey Publishing Vol. 1 408 pp. \n* Moolenbeek, R.G. 1995. ''Gastropods (Gastropoda)''. pp.&nbsp;24\u2013186 in Dance, S.P. (ed). Seashells of Eastern Arabia. Dubai : Motivate Publishing.\n* Higo, S., Callomon, P. & Goto, Y. 1999. ''Catalogue and Bibliography of the Marine Shell-bearing Mollusca of Japan''. Japan : Elle Scientific Publications 749 pp\n* Wilson, B. 2002. ''A Handbook to Australian Seashells on Seashores East to West and North to South''. Sydney : Reed New Holland 185 pp\n* Poppe G.T., Tagaro S.P. & Dekker H. (2006) ''The Seguenziidae, Chilodontidae, Trochidae, Calliostomatidae and Solariellidae of the Philippine Islands''. Visaya Supplement 2: 1\u2013228. page(s): 102\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gastropods.com|key=5|id=2425|title=''Stomatia phymotis''|access-date=16 January 2019}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q7618730}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stomatia Phymotis}}\n[[Category:Stomatia|phymotis]]\n[[Category:Molluscs described in 1779]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| taxon = Stomatia phymotis\n| image = Stomatia phymotis 01.JPG\n| image_caption = Five views of a shell of ''Stomatia phymotis''\n| authority =  (Hebling, 1779) <ref>Helbling, G.S. 1779. ''Beitr\u00e4ge zur Kenntnis neuer seltener Konchylien. 102-125, pl. 2 in Abhandlungen einer Privatgesellschaft in B\u00f6hmen zur Aufnahme der Mathematik, der v\u00e4terlandischen Geschichte, und der Naturgeschichte.'' Prag : Ignaz Edlen von Born Vol. 4</ref>\n| synonyms_ref = \n| synonyms =\n* ''Haliotis imperforata'' <small>Gmelin, 1791</small>\n* ''Stomatia australis'' <small>A. Adams, 1850</small>\n* ''Stomatia obscurata'' <small>Lamarck, 1822</small>\n* ''Stomatia (Miraconcha) obscura'' <small>Sowerby, G.B. III, 1874</small>\n* ''Stomax furonculus'' <small>Montfort</small>\n| display_parents = 3\n}}\n\n'''''Stomatia phymotis''''', common name the '''swollen stomatella''', is a [[species]] of [[sea snail]], a marine [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Trochidae]], the top snails.<ref name=\"WoRMS\">{{WRMS species|216287|''Stomatia phymotis'' (Hebling, 1779)||1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe size of the shell varies between 7&nbsp;mm and 35&nbsp;mm. The lengthened, solid shell is ear-shaped. It has a scalar spire. The [[body whorl]] descends very deeply. The shell is lusterless, red, marked at the [[Suture (anatomy)|suture]], keel and base with olive or brown articulated with white. The surface is very rough, with a strong double nodulous keel at the middle of the [[Whorl (mollusc)|whorl]], several nodose spiral riblets and threads below it, strongly. The shell is plicate or puckered below the sutures. The [[Aperture (mollusc)|aperture]] is irregular-oval and nacreous inside.\n\nThere is considerable variation in both form and color.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/manualconch12tryorich H.A. Pilsbry (1890) Manual of Conchology XII; Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia, 1890]</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThis marine species occurs in the [[Red Sea]], Central and East Indian Ocean, East India, Indo-Malaysia, [[Oceania]], the [[Philippines]], [[Japan]], [[Australia]] (Northern Territory, Queensland, Western Australia) and [[Indonesia]].<ref>{{cite book\n |url=https://www.amazon.com/Siput-Kerang-Indonesia-Indonesian-Shells/dp/B0010AHVB0\n |first1=Bunjamin |last1=Dharma\n |year=1988\n |title=Siput dan kerang Indonesia (Indonesian Shells)\n |volume=I. [A up to Olividae]\n |pages=111 pp\n |publisher=PT. Sarana Graha |location=[[Jakarta]]\n |accessdate=2017-03-14 |language=id,en }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Gmelin, J.F. & Linnaeus, C. 1791. ''Caroli a Linn\u00e9 Systema Naturae per regna tria naturae, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentis, synonymis, locis.'' Editio decima tertia aucta, reformata. Lipsiae : G.E. Beer.\n* Adams, A. 1850. ''An arrangement of Stomatellidae, including the characters of a new genus Cumingia, with some additional generic characters.'' Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London 1850(18): 29\u201340, pl. 8\n* Melvill, J.C. & Standen, R. 1901. ''The Mollusca of the Persian Gulf, Gulf of Oman, and the Arabian Sea, as evidenced mainly through the collections of Mr. F.W. Townsend, 1893\u20131900; with descriptions of new species''. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London 1901(ii): 327-460 pls xxi-xxiv \n* Allan, J. 1935. ''Australian shells: ear shells and wide-mouthed shells''. Australian Museum Magazine 5(9): 320\u2013324, 5 figs\n* Cotton, B.C. 1945. ''Southern Australian Gastropoda. Part 1. Streptoneura''. Transactions of the Royal Society of South Australia 69(1): 150-171\n* Cotton, B.C. 1959. ''South Australian Mollusca. Archaeogastropoda''. Handbook of the Flora and Fauna of South Australia. Adelaide : South Australian Government Printer 449 pp\n* Maes, V.O. 1967. ''The littoral marine mollusks of Cocos-Keeling Islands (Indian Ocean).'' Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia 119: 93-217\n* Cernohorsky, W.O. 1974. ''Type specimens of Mollusca in the University Zoological Museum Copenhagen''. Records of the Auckland Institute and Museum 11: 143-195\n* Sharabati, D. 1984. ''Red Sea Shells''. London : KPI Limited 128 pp.\n* Wells, F.E. & Bryce, C.W. 1988. ''Seashells of Western Australia''. Perth : Western Australian Museum 207 pp.\n* Wilson, B. 1993. ''Australian Marine Shells. Prosobranch Gastropod